   ABSTRACT    
   &nbsp;   
   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Moringa oleifera and Cissus quadrangularis are two medicinal plants widely used in traditional systems of medicine due to their diverse therapeutic properties. This review highlights their Pharmacognostics characteristics, phytochemical constituents, pharmacological activities, extraction methods, and toxicological profiles. Moringa oleifera is rich in alkaloids, flavonoids, phenolic compounds, vitamins, and minerals, exhibiting antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, antidiabetic, cardioprotective, and wound-healing activities. Cissus quadrangularis contains phytosterols, flavonoids, triterpenoids, and ascorbic acid, contributing to its bone-healing, anti-obesity, anti-ulcer, antidiabetic, antioxidant, and neuroprotective effects. Various extraction techniques, including maceration, Soxhlet extraction, microwave-assisted extraction, and ultrasound-assisted extraction, have been employed to isolate bioactive compounds from these plants. Toxicological studies indicate a favorable safety profile for both species. The synergistic therapeutic potential of Moringa oleifera and Cissus quadrangularis suggests promising applications in modern herbal medicine, nutraceuticals, and polyherbal formulations for managing chronic diseases and promoting overall health.  
   &nbsp;   

   Key words:        Moringa oleifera, Cissus quadrangularis, Phytochemistry, Antioxidants, Bone Healing, Herbal Therapeutics.

